Stopped into Lou's for some lunch this past Sunday. I had been to Moneygun in the past for a stiff drink and happy-hour hangs, but hadn't actually been to Lou's; I had made a grave mistake by not visiting before. A friend and I were looking for a casual lunch spot around the West Loop, where things can get stuffy in a hurry. This fit the bill perfectly. The ambiance is fantastic, transitioning from an old-school diner in front, to an open and airy back room and adjacent patio. I felt as if I could lounge there for hours. On top of that, the staff was accommodating, quick, and chatty (in a warm, friendly way). I had the patty melt and it was well executed - nice caramelized onions, a juicy patty, and crisp rye bread made it a filling Sunday-Scaries treat. I'll absolutely be back, and I recommend you drop by too, if you're in the need of a laid-back lunch spot - or a bright and airy place to have some craft cocktails and honest-to-goodness grub.

Went for a “wine” down drink after a hard day’s work and I felt like it was an issue with me being there. There was an event going on in the back there were no event signs so no way to tell initially because I’ve only stopped by there once before. Asked the waitress if I could sit she said yes. Then the lady from the front who already seemed a bit annoyed came to tell me they were having an event so I needed to sit at the bar which was quite crowded no one was friendly but the waitress.. it wasn’t an inviting experience at all. The room was small so I felt like being at that bar while there was another event felt like I was invading someone else’s space and I think they felt the same. I won’t be back there. Staff was also pretty relaxed about my friend's toddlers that also come to celebrate my birthday! My only regret is not remember our server's name so that I could do a shout-out to him! Had a great time!

I am very disappointed with St. Lou’s. Usually, the food is delicious. Tonight, a friend and I both ordered a $9 mixed green salad. It was a very over dressed plate of greens. No croutons, nothing added. Just mixed green and so much dressing I couldn’t eat it. Ridiculous. The biscuits were tasty, as usual. The service was also slow and disjointed - we waited for 20 minutes to close the tab. I work in the area and use St. Lou’s for work events frequently in the summer. Not anymore! There are waaay better places for the price, for tasty food and drinks.

Went here for a private event in the patio area hosted by Jagermeister.  This is a cute casual restaurant in the front but has an awesome bar and Patio in the back with bocce ball.  If you're headed to the patio or outdoor yard, enter either through the front of the restaurant or on the left side of the restaurant, there is a door that will lead you straight into the patio.  You will walk past live plants that are planted in rows of gutters mounted on the wall. This is so impressive and an awesome idea that I might want to attempt it in my house.  When you step into the bar area you are greeted by a long bar that is fully stocked with many options .  The patio area is awesome, bright, airy, and fun. Lots of tables and even some stadium seating so that you can watch your friends while they play bocce ball.  A perfect place to meet friends for a drink or for brunch.  We had pulled pork, macaroni and cheese, corn that was grilled on the barbecue and some homemade biscuits that tasted out-of-this-world!  Can't wait to come back for brunch or lunch!

But honestly even with those faults counted the place still deserved 4 stars, the meal itself was fantastic, the chef definitely knows their stuff. The drinks were... OK, the staff although fairly slow were very friendly and courteous which goes a long way.  I'd be happy to recommend this place to anyone.

A great lunch spot for a Meat and Three (choice of three sides) served cafeteria style that goes well beyond cafeteria food. Dinner is full service that offers amazing beers and cocktails. Food is absolutely amazing. Drink selection is absolutely amazing. The drink and food baskets are worth it while you sit on one of Chicago's most gorgeous backyards. Definitely a place to get some grub and drinks before you head over to its attached cocktail bar, Moneygun(which i also highly recommend).

Interesting spot. Their new patio is a pleasant affair but the breadth of beverages is surprisingly limited.  They offer a half decent selection of beers, but only one white and one red by the glass and that choice appears to be what ever they have open at the time. To compound the situation the choice of cocktails borders on prohibition.  So all-in-all St Lou's Assembly is currently half pregnant.
